'''Action Christian National''' ('''ACN''') was a [[White nationalism|white nationalist]] [[political party]] in [[Namibia]] (formerly [[South West Africa]]).<ref name="BurnellWare2007">{{cite book|last1=Burnell|first1=Peter J.|last2=Ware|first2=Allan|title=Funding Democratization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bOdjsqqPfgcC|accessdate=20 September 2012|year=2007|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=9781412806008|page=208}}</ref> The ACN was established in 1989 to enable whites to participate in the elections.<ref>{{cite book|author=Elena Torreguitar|title=National Liberation Movements in Office: Forging Democracy with African Adjectives in Namibia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH2RNl42kIMC&pg=PA483|accessdate=6 May 2016|year=2009|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-3-631-57995-4|page=483}}</ref> It used to be aligned with the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] of [[South Africa]]. In the [[Namibian parliamentary election, 1989]] that elected the [[members of the Constituent Assembly of Namibia]], ACN won three seats.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hubbard|first1=Dianne|last2=Ramsbotham|first2=Delia|last3=Marais|first3=Nicky|title=Advocacy in Action. A guide to influencing decision-making in Namibia|url=http://www.lac.org.na/projects/grap/Pdf/advguide.pdf|year=2004|publisher=Legal Assistance Centre|location=Windhoek|isbn=99916-765-9-7|page=139|access-date=2012-09-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102210930/http://www.lac.org.na/projects/grap/Pdf/advguide.pdf|archive-date=2016-01-02|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> The party's chairman was [[Jan de Wet]]. It subsequently became the [[Monitor Action Group]].
