[[File:Despeje.png|thumb|400px|Map of El Caguán DMZ]]

The '''El Caguán DMZ''' ({{lang-es|Zona de Distensión, zona de despeje de San Vicente del Caguán}}) was a [[demilitarized zone]] of 42,000&nbsp;km² in southern [[Colombia]] authorized by the government of President [[Andres Pastrana Arango|Andrés Pastrana]] to negotiate a [[FARC-Government peace process (1999-2002)|peace process]] with the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC-EP). It existed for three years, from 1999 until 2002.

On October 8, 1998, then presidential candidate Andrés Pastrana agreed with FARC commanders to create a [[demilitarized zone]] in the region of El Caguán river basin, a jungle region in south central Colombia made up by the municipalities of [[Vista Hermosa, Meta|Vista Hermosa]], [[La Macarena, Meta|La Macarena]], [[La Uribe]] and [[Mesetas]] in [[Meta Department]], and [[San Vicente del Caguán]] in [[Caquetá Department]] to negotiate a possible peace process.

