{{Infobox organization | name = Open Technology Fund | logo = | caption = | abbreviation = OTF | formation = {{Start date|2012}} | type = | status = | purpose = The funding of [[Internet censorship circumvention]] and [[Internet privacy]] technologies<ref name="about-the-program"/> | headquarters = 2025 M Street NW, Suite 300 | location = [[Washington, D.C.]] | coords = | region_served = | membership = | language = | owner= [[Radio Free Asia]] ([[Broadcasting Board of Governors]]) | parent_organization= | leader_title = Director | leader_name = [[Dan Meredith]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Team|url=https://www.opentech.fund/about/people/team|publisher=Open Technology Fund|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> | affiliations = | budget = | num_staff = | num_volunteers = | website = {{url|https://www.opentech.fund}} }}
The '''Open Technology Fund''' ('''OTF''') is a [[U.S. Government]] funded program created in 2012 at [[Radio Free Asia]] to support global [[Internet freedom]] technologies. Its mission is to "[utilize] available funds to support projects that develop open and accessible technologies to circumvent [[censorship]] and [[surveillance]], and thus promote [[human rights]] and open societies".<ref name="about-the-program">{{cite web|title=About the program|url=https://www.opentech.fund/about/program|publisher=Open Technology Fund|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>
==History== The Open Technology Fund was created in 2012.<ref name="about-the-program"/> According to US journalist [[Eli Lake]], the idea for the creation of the Open Technology Fund was the result of a policy advocated by [[Hillary Clinton]] when she was the [[United States Secretary of State|U.S. Secretary of State]].<ref name="Lake-2015-09-18"/> Lake has written that Clinton's policy was "heavily influenced by the [[Internet activism]] that helped organize the [[2009 Iranian presidential election protests|green revolution in Iran in 2009]] and other [[Arab Spring|revolutions in the Arab world in 2010 and 2011]]".<ref name="Lake-2015-09-18">{{cite web|last1=Lake|first1=Eli|title=Government Is Fighting Itself on Encryption|url=http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-09-18/government-is-fighting-itself-on-encryption|website=Bloomberg View|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|type=Column|accessdate=15 February 2016|date=18 September 2015}} Note: The author uses "Open Whisper" when referring to [[Open Whisper Systems]].</ref>
In September 2014, the Open Technology Fund worked with [[Google]] and [[Dropbox (service)|Dropbox]] to create an organization called Simply Secure to help improve the usability of privacy tools.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rushe|first1=Dominic|title=Google and Dropbox launch Simply Secure to improve online security|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/sep/18/google-dropbox-simply-secure-security-tech|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=18 September 2014}}</ref>
==Organization and funding== The Open Technology Fund reports to Radio Free Asia's president, who in turn reports to the [[Broadcasting Board of Governors]] (BBG).<ref name="about-the-program"/> The OTF is sustained by annual grants from the BBG, which originate from yearly U.S. Congressional appropriations for State, Foreign Operations, and Related Programs.<ref name="about-the-program"/> According to the OTF, it works together with other publicly funded programs to fulfill a U.S. Congressional mandate to sustain and increase global [[freedom of information]] on the Internet with public funds.<ref name="about-the-program"/>
==Projects== {{As of|2016|02}}, the Open Technology Fund supports 83 projects, consisting of over 2&nbsp;700 developers, technologists, and translators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Results|url=https://www.opentech.fund/results|publisher=Open Technology Fund|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> Notable projects that the OTF has supported include [[The Tor Project, Inc|The Tor Project]], [[Open Whisper Systems]], [[Cryptocat]], [[GlobaLeaks]], [[Tor2web]], [[The Guardian Project (software)|The Guardian Project]], [[Citizen Lab]], [[Commotion Wireless]], [[Lantern (software)|Lantern]], [[Serval Project]], [[Briar (software)|Briar]], [[NoScript]], [[Qubes OS]], and [[Tails (operating system)|Tails]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Projects|url=https://www.opentech.fund/projects|publisher=Open Technology Fund|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>
The OTF funds third party [[Information technology security audit|audits]] for all of the [[source code|code]] related projects that it supports.<ref name="code-audits"/> It has also offered to fund audits of "non-OTF supported projects that are in use by individuals and organizations under threat of censorship/surveillance".<ref name="code-audits"/> Notable projects whose audits the OTF has sponsored include Cryptocat,<ref>{{cite web|first1=Alban|last1=Diquet|first2=David|last2=Thiel|first3=Scott|last3=Stender|title=Open Technology Fund CryptoCat iOS Application Penetration Test|url=https://isecpartners.github.io/publications/iSEC_Cryptocat_iOS.pdf|publisher=iSEC Partners|accessdate=13 February 2016|format=PDF|date=7 February 2014}}</ref> Commotion Wireless,<ref name="isecpartners-2013"/> [[TextSecure]],<ref name="isecpartners-2013">{{cite web|title=Working with the Open Technology Fund |url=https://isecpartners.github.io/2013/10/14/open-tech-fund-report-release.html |first1=Tom |last1=Ritter |publisher=iSEC Partners |date=14 October 2013 |accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> GlobaLeaks,<ref name="isecpartners-2013"/> [[MediaWiki]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Steipp|first1=Chris|title=Improving the security of our users on Wikimedia sites|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2015/04/20/improving-security-for-our-users/|website=Wikimedia Blog|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|accessdate=13 February 2016|date=20 April 2015}}</ref> OpenPGP.js,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heiderich|first1=Mario|last2=Kotowicz|first2=Krzysztof|last3=Magazinius|first3=Jonas|last4=Antesberger|first4=Franz|title=Pentest-Report OpenPGP.js 02.2014|url=https://cure53.de/pentest-report_openpgpjs.pdf|publisher=Cure53|accessdate=14 February 2016|format=PDF|date=February 2014}}</ref> [[Nitrokey]],<ref>{{Cite web|last1=McDevitt|first1=Dan|title = Nitrokey Storage Firmware and Hardware Security Audits|url = https://www.opentech.fund/article/nitrokey-storage-firmware-and-hardware-security-audits|publisher = Open Technology Fund|accessdate =15 February 2016|date=2 October 2015}}</ref> and [[Ricochet (software)|Ricochet]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cox|first1=Joseph|title='Ricochet', the Messenger That Beats Metadata, Passes Security Audit|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/ricochet-encrypted-messenger-tackles-metadata-problem-head-on|website=Motherboard|publisher=Vice Media LLC|accessdate=17 February 2016|date=17 February 2016}}</ref> The OTF also matched donations that were made toward the auditing of [[TrueCrypt]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Kenneth|last2=Green|first2=Matthew|title=IsTrueCryptAuditedYet?|url=http://istruecryptauditedyet.com/|publisher=Open Crypto Audit Project|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=21 January 2014}}</ref> In December 2014, the OTF reported that it had funded more than 30 technology code audits over the past three years, identifying 185 privacy and security vulnerabilities in both OTF and non-OTF-funded projects.<ref name="code-audits">{{cite web|last1=Hurley|first1=Chad|title=Code Audits are Good. Making Code Audits Public is Better|url=https://www.opentech.fund/article/code-audits-are-good-making-code-audits-public-better|publisher=Open Technology Fund|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=10 December 2014}}</ref>
In December 2015, The Tor Project announced that the OTF will be sponsoring a [[bug bounty program]] that will be coordinated by [[HackerOne]].<ref name="tor-bounty">{{cite web|last1=Cox|first1=Joseph|title=The Tor Project Is Starting a Bug Bounty Program|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/the-tor-project-is-starting-a-bug-bounty-program|website=Motherboard|publisher=Vice Media LLC|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Conditt|first1=Jessica|title=Tor plans to launch a bug bounty program|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/12/31/tor-plans-to-launch-a-bug-bounty-program/|website=Engadget|publisher=AOL Inc.|accessdate=14 February 2016|date=31 December 2015}}</ref> The program will initially be invite-only and will focus on finding vulnerabilities that are specific to The Tor Project's applications.<ref name="tor-bounty"/>
